1. What is a Callback?

A callback is a function that is passed as an argument to another function and is executed later.

Think of it like this:

"After finishing this task, call this function."

Basic Example
function greet(name) {
    console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
}

function processUser(callback) {
    callback("Priya");
}

processUser(greet);
Output
Hello Priya
How it Works
processUser(greet)
        │
        ▼
callback("Priya")
        │
        ▼
greet("Priya")
        │
        ▼
Hello Priya
Callback with Anonymous Function

Instead of creating a separate function:

function processUser(callback) {
    callback("Priya");
}

processUser(function(name) {
    console.log(`Welcome ${name}`);
});
Output
Welcome Priya
Callback with Arrow Function
function processUser(callback) {
    callback("Priya");
}

processUser((name) => {
    console.log(`Hello ${name}`);
});
Output
Hello Priya
2. Why Do We Use Callbacks?

Callbacks allow one function to decide what happens after another function finishes.

Example:

function calculate(a, b, operation) {
    operation(a, b);
}

calculate(10, 20, function(x, y) {
    console.log(x + y);
});
Output
30
Multiple Callbacks
function calculate(a, b, operation) {
    operation(a, b);
}

function add(x, y) {
    console.log(x + y);
}

function multiply(x, y) {
    console.log(x * y);
}

calculate(10, 20, add);
calculate(10, 20, multiply);
Output
30
200
3. Synchronous vs Asynchronous
Synchronous

Tasks execute one after another.

console.log("Start");

console.log("Learning JavaScript");

console.log("End");
Output
Start
Learning JavaScript
End

Flow:

Start
  ↓
Learning JavaScript
  ↓
End
Asynchronous

Some tasks take time (API calls, file downloads, timers).

JavaScript doesn't wait.

console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Inside Timeout");
}, 2000);

console.log("End");
Output
Start
End
Inside Timeout
Why?

setTimeout() schedules the callback to run after 2 seconds, while JavaScript continues executing the next line.

Understanding setTimeout
setTimeout(function() {
    console.log("Executed after 3 seconds");
}, 3000);

Output after 3 seconds:

Executed after 3 seconds
Example
function orderFood(callback) {

    console.log("Ordering food...");

    setTimeout(() => {
        console.log("Food is ready");
        callback();
    }, 3000);

}

function eatFood() {
    console.log("Eating food");
}

orderFood(eatFood);
Output
Ordering food...
(3-second delay)
Food is ready
Eating food
4. Real-World Example – Download File
function downloadFile(callback) {

    console.log("Downloading file...");

    setTimeout(() => {
        console.log("Download Complete");
        callback();
    }, 2000);

}

function openFile() {
    console.log("Opening File");
}

downloadFile(openFile);
Output
Downloading file...
Download Complete
Opening File
5. Callback Hell ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Sometimes callbacks become deeply nested.

setTimeout(() => {

    console.log("Step 1");

    setTimeout(() => {

        console.log("Step 2");

        setTimeout(() => {

            console.log("Step 3");

        }, 1000);

    }, 1000);

}, 1000);

This produces a "pyramid" shape:

setTimeout
    └── setTimeout
            └── setTimeout

This is called Callback Hell because the code becomes difficult to read and maintain.

Why Callback Hell is a Problem
Difficult to read
Hard to debug
Hard to maintain
Error handling becomes complicated

This is why JavaScript introduced Promises and later async/await.

Real-World Example – Bank Transaction
function verifyOTP(callback) {

    console.log("Verifying OTP...");

    setTimeout(() => {
        console.log("OTP Verified");
        callback();
    }, 2000);

}

function transferMoney() {
    console.log("Money Transferred");
}

verifyOTP(transferMoney);
Output
Verifying OTP...
OTP Verified
Money Transferred
Common Mistakes
❌ Calling the Function Instead of Passing It

Wrong:

function greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
}

setTimeout(greet(), 2000);

greet() runs immediately.

Correct:

setTimeout(greet, 2000);
❌ Forgetting the Callback Parameter

Wrong:

function processUser() {
    callback();
}

Correct:

function processUser(callback) {
    callback();
}
